er integration. Fix: make `applied_stack(Some(id))` use an unpruned/by-ref lookup, then keep this caller small.\"},\"[REDACTED:entropy]\":{\"completed\":\"**Findings**\\n\\n- `[REDACTED:path]`  \\n  `create_independent_branch()` now re-reads the new stack through `applied_stack()`, which is backed by pruned `head_info()`. The old `stack_details(ctx, Some(new_stack_id))` had a stack-id/ref fallback, so it could still resolve stacks not visible from current `HEAD`[REDACTED:path] This can create the branch, print `Created new independent branch ...`, then fail before committing.  \\n  Suggested fix: don’t use pruned `applied_stack()` here. Build the target from returned `new_ref`, or add an unpruned stack-by-id/ref lookup matching the old fallback. Move the human “Created...” print after the target is resolved.\\n\\n- `[REDACTED:path]` and `[REDACTED:path]`  \\n  Old code tolerated unsupported/bad stacks by filtering `stack_details(...).ok()`. New `applied_stacks(ctx)?` fails the whole command if any head-info stack/segment cannot convert, even when the requested target branch is fine.  \\n  Suggested fix: keep target selection tolerant: skip unconvertible stacks before prompting/defaulting, or convert only the matched stack after resolving the branch hint.\"}},\"timed_out\":false}","tool_name":"wait_agent","tool_kind":"housekeeping","tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-06-03T12:16:56.922Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]"}}}